=========================================
VARIADIC TEMPLATES (C++11) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is a Variadic Template?
------------------------------
- Variadic templates (C++11 feature) allow a template to accept
  ANY number of arguments.
- It is used when number of parameters is unknown at compile time.
- Uses "parameter packs".

-----------------------------------------

2. Syntax
---------
template<typename... Args>
void func(Args... args);

- Args...  → template parameter pack
- args...  → function parameter pack expansion

-----------------------------------------

3. Why Variadic Templates are needed?
-------------------------------------
Before C++11:
- We had to write multiple overloaded functions:

func(int)
func(int, int)
func(int, int, int)

Problems:
- Code duplication
- Not scalable
- Maintenance issues

Solution:
- One variadic template handles all cases

-----------------------------------------

4. Basic Example
----------------

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void print() {
    cout << endl;
}

template<typename T, typename... Args>
void print(T first, Args... rest) {
    cout << first << " ";
    print(rest...);
}

int main() {
    print(1, 2, 3, 4, "hello");
}

-----------------------------------------

5. How it works (IMPORTANT)
--------------------------
This works using RECURSION:

Step-by-step:
print(1,2,3)
→ prints 1
→ calls print(2,3)
→ prints 2
→ calls print(3)
→ prints 3
→ calls print()
→ stops (base case)

-----------------------------------------

6. Base Case (VERY IMPORTANT)
----------------------------
You MUST define a base case:

void print() {
    // stops recursion
}

Without base case → compile error / infinite recursion

-----------------------------------------

7. Pack Expansion
-----------------
Example:
template<typename... Args>
void show(Args... args) {
    (cout << ... << args);  // C++17 fold expression (advanced)
}

C++11 version uses recursion instead.

-----------------------------------------

8. Real-world Usage
-------------------
- STL: make_shared, make_unique
- tuple
- emplace_back
- factory functions
- logging frameworks
- forwarding functions

-----------------------------------------

9. Example: Logging Function
---------------------------

template<typename... Args>
void log(Args... args) {
    print(args...);
}

log("Error:", 404, "Not Found");

-----------------------------------------

10. Example: sum of values
--------------------------

template<typename T>
T sum(T x) {
    return x;
}

template<typename T, typename... Args>
T sum(T first, Args... rest) {
    return first + sum(rest...);
}

-----------------------------------------

11. Advantages
-------------
✔ Works with any number of arguments
✔ Reduces function overloading
✔ Used heavily in STL
✔ Enables generic programming
✔ Core part of modern C++ libraries

-----------------------------------------

12. Disadvantages
-----------------
- Hard to debug compile errors
- Recursive implementation complexity
- Can reduce readability if overused

-----------------------------------------

13. Interview Key Points
------------------------
- Introduced in C++11
- Uses parameter packs (Args...)
- Requires recursion + base case (C++11 style)
- Used in STL internals (make_shared, emplace)
- Foundation of modern template metaprogramming

